# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: benny-meyer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Born in Collinsville, Illinois, he batted and threw right-handed, stood 5 feet 10 inches (1.78 m) tall and weighed 170 pounds (77 kg).
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher came to the Giants in 1909 after only one season of minor league experience, and became the club's regular shortstop two years later.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] He played in four World Series while performing for McGraw (1911, 1912, 1913 and 1917).
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Traded to the Philadelphia Phillies in the midst of the 1920 season, he retired after the 1922 campaign with 1,534 hits, 32 home runs, 676 RBI and a .277 batting average.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher is the Giants' career leader in being hit by pitches (132) and ranks 29th on the MLB career list (141) for the same statistic.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] In 1923 he replaced Kaiser Wilhelm as manager of the seventh-place Phillies and led the club through four losing seasons, bookended by last-place finishes in 1923 and 1926.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] In October 1926, he was replaced by Stuffy McInnis.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher then began a 19-year tenure (1927–1945) as a coach for the Yankees, where, beginning with the legendary 1927 team, he would participate on ten American League pennant winners and nine World Series champions.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Vincent's Hospital in Greenwich Village on September 20, 1929 with a case of influenza on recommendation of Dr.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] With that, Fletcher and Charley O'Leary would take control of the team in his absence.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Despite a blood transfusion on September 23, Ed Barrow stated that the health of the Yankees' manager was in bad shape due to erysipelas and that a priest had been called.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher and O'Leary, coaching the Yankees at a game at Fenway Park in Boston, Massachusetts on September 25, were told by team secretary Mark Roth that Huggins died in Manhattan.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher, O'Leary and pitching coach Bob Shawkey felt heartbroken about their passing and kept it quiet when they were notified on the news.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Players for the Boston Red Sox were made aware as well about what had happened and the game had become quiet.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] After the fifth inning, players from both teams went to home plate with the umpires and watched as the American flag at Fenway was lowered to half-mast in honor of Huggins.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher, enthralled with the opportunity Huggins gave him, turned down three opportunities to become a manager for different American League teams to be able to stay with Huggins.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher, speaking for the team, who also talked to the press, chose to comment on the upcoming World Series and predicted that the Philadelphia Athletics would win it over the Chicago Cubs.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher and O'Leary took a train from Boston after the game for Washington D.C. but were going to attend the funeral of Huggins first.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Immediate speculation was that Fletcher would replace Huggins as the manager for the 1930 season.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher was considered the likeliest candidate and that while O'Leary was given the position as manager for the rest of the 1929 season, he felt Jacob Ruppert would put in Fletcher to continue the clubhouse Huggins had built.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Huggins' funeral was held in Manhattan at the Church of the Transfiguration on September 27.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher, Shawkey and O'Leary, along with Babe Ruth, Herb Pennock, Lou Gehrig, Earle Combs and Tony Lazzeri served as pallbearers of their manager's coffin before it was sent to Cincinnati, Ohio by train for burial.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] On October 17, 1929, Ruppert announced that Shawkey would become the manager of the Yankees for 1930 after Fletcher rejected the position.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Ruppert noted that Huggins asked the owner c.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] 1924–1925 that his successor should be decided and pressured him to choose Fletcher.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Before the death of Huggins, Ruppert asked Fletcher to take the position and he refused the position then.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Following Huggins' death, Ruppert approached Fletcher with the option to manage in 1930, but rejected it a third time, stating that he would rather be a coach and not have the extra responsibility of being the manager.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher, who had been serving as a part-time manager in 1945 with Joe McCarthy ill, suffered a heart attack on September 10 during a game against the Cleveland Indians while standing in the third base coach box.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] He suffered a second heart attack and he was rushed to St.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Elizabeth's Hospital in Washington Heights, Manhattan, where he was placed in serious condition.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Robert Walsh, who was serving as the team's physician told Fletcher that the heart attack was not a serious one but that he would have to stop coaching for the 1945 season to recover from it.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] At that time period, Fletcher had been considered a candidate to manage the team in the 1946 season if McCarthy chose to retire.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher suffered a third heart attack and was considered out of danger by September 18.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] However, he told the Yankees that he intended to retire after the 1945 season due to losing his interest for the travel and preparation for each season.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] He planned on moving to California and purchasing home in retirement.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] With a large inheritance from his father, a banker from Collinsville, he felt that he could move on.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher would also end up suffering from pneumonia at the hospital, but by the beginning of October 1945, he was able to have visitors, with McCarthy the first to visit.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] On October 12, 1945, McCarthy announced that Bill Dickey would replace Fletcher as the second-level coach on the Yankees.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher was released from the hospital on October 30 to his home in New York a week before he would leave for his home in Collinsville.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher died of another heart attack on February 6, 1950 while sitting in a car in Los Angeles, California with his wife, Irene on vacation from Collinsville.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] His funeral was held at Presbyterian Church in Collinsville on February 12.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Fletcher would be buried in Glenwood Cemetery.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] McCarthy visited for the funeral, staying in St.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] Louis, Missouri before attending the service.
[src:benny-meyer/art-fletcher] It was while in the area he learned about the death of former teammate Kiki Cuyler.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:benny-meyer/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:benny-meyer/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:benny-meyer/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] In four seasons he played in 310 major league games and had 1,041 at bats, 146 runs, 276 hits, 29 doubles, 17 triples, 7 home runs, 84 RBIs, 46 stolen bases, 158 walks, .265 batting average, .365 on-base percentage, .346 slugging percentage, 360 total bases and 31 sacrifice hits.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] After retiring as a player, he worked as a coach for the Philadelphia Phillies under manager Art Fletcher.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] He served as a non-playing captain in 1924.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] He coached with the Detroit Tigers under manager Bucky Harris.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] He developed a reputation for his loudness as a coach for Detroit and was the subject of an article in *The Sporting Life* in 1929.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] He managed the Grand Rapids Chicks in 1945.
[src:benny-meyer/benny-meyer] He died in Festus, Missouri, at the age of 89.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The **Brooklyn Dodgers** were a Major League Baseball team founded in 1883 as the **Brooklyn Grays**.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1884, it became a member of the American Association as the **Brooklyn Atlantics** before joining the National League in 1890.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] They remained in Brooklyn, New York, until 1957, after which the team moved to Los Angeles, where it continues its history as the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] That same year, the Dodgers' longtime rival, the New York Giants, moved to San Francisco and became the San Francisco Giants.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The "Dodgers" team name is a shortened form of one of their former names, the **Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers.** "Trolley dodgers" is a nickname for Brooklyn residents who had to avoid being hit by the city's fast-moving trolleys while crossing their lines.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers later earned the respectful nickname **Dem Bums**.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers played in two stadiums in South Brooklyn, each named Washington Park, and at Eastern Park in the neighborhood of Brownsville before moving to Ebbets Field in the neighborhood of Crown Heights in 1912.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The team is noted for signing Jackie Robinson in 1947 as the first black player in the modern major leagues.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Brooklyn Dodgers had an overall win–loss record of 5,624–5,290–133 (.515) during their 68 years in Brooklyn.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Eight former Brooklyn Dodgers players were elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Many of the clubs represented at the first convention of the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) were from Brooklyn, including the Atlantic, Eckford, and Excelsior clubs that combined to dominate play for most of the 1860s.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Brooklyn helped make baseball commercial, as the locale of the first paid admission games, a series of three all star contests matching New York and Brooklyn in 1858.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Brooklyn also featured the first two enclosed baseball grounds, the Union Grounds and the Capitoline Grounds; enclosed, dedicated ballparks accelerated the evolution from amateurism to professionalism.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Despite the early success of Brooklyn clubs in the NABBP, which were officially amateur until 1869, they fielded weak teams in the succeeding National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NAPBBP), the first professional league formed in 1871.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Excelsiors no longer challenged for the amateur championship after the Civil War (1861–1865) and never entered the professional NAPBBP (aka NA).
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Eckfords and Atlantics declined to join until 1872 and thereby lost their best players; the Eckfords survived only one season and the Atlantics four, with losing teams.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The National League (NL) replaced the NAPBBP in 1876 and granted exclusive territories to its eight members, excluding the Atlantics in favor of the Mutual Club of New York who had shared home grounds with the Atlantics.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] When the Mutuals were expelled by the league, the Hartford club moved in, the press dubbing them the **Brooklyn Hartfords**, and played its home games at Union Grounds in 1877 before disbanding.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The team currently known as the Dodgers was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne, who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Byrne arranged to build a grandstand on a lot bounded by Third Street, Fourth Avenue, Fifth Street, and Fifth Avenue, and named it Washington Park in honor of first president George Washington.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Nicknamed by reporters the **"Grays"** for their uniforms, the team played in the minor league Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs that first season.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Doyle became the first team manager, and they drew 6,431 fans to their first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton, New Jersey team.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Grays won the league title after the Camden Merritt club in New Jersey disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Grays were invited to join the two-year-old professional circuit, the American Association (founded 1882) to compete with the eight-year-old NL for the 1884 season.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] They lost the 1889 championship tournament to the New York Giants and tied the 1890 championship with Louisville.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Their success during this period was partly attributed to their having absorbed skilled players from the defunct AA New York Metropolitans and one-year Players' League entry the Brooklyn Ward's Wonders.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The middle years of the decade were disappointing, a slump the Spalding Guide rather primly ascribed to management tolerating drunkenness among the players.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Over the 1890s, Charles Ebbets accumulated shares in the club, owning 80% of it by decade's end.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Other shares were held by Harry Von der Horst, owner of the Baltimore Orioles team that won consecutive championships in 1894, 1895, and 1896, and Orioles manager Ned Hanlon.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1899, Von der Horst and Hanlon moved most of the Orioles' stars from Baltimore to join the Grays (Bridegrooms) in Brooklyn; Hanlon became the team's manager.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The press, inspired by the popular circus act The Hanlons' Superba, dubbed the new combined team the **Brooklyn Superbas**.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1899 and in 1900, they were the champions of the National League.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The name Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers was first used to describe the team in 1895.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Some sources erroneously report that the name "Trolley Dodgers" referred to pedestrians avoiding fast cars on street car tracks that bordered Eastern Park on two sides.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] However, Eastern Park was not bordered by street-level trolley lines that had to be "dodged" by pedestrians.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The name "Trolley Dodgers" implied the dangers posed by trolley cars in Brooklyn generally, which in 1892, began the switch from horse-power to electrical power, which made them much faster, and were hence regarded as more dangerous.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The name was later shortened to **Brooklyn Dodgers**.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] All of these nicknames were used by fans and newspaper sportswriters to describe the team, often concurrently, but not in any official capacity.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The team's legal name was the **Brooklyn Base Ball Club**.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The "Trolley Dodgers" nickname was used throughout this period, along with other nicknames, by fans and sports writers of the day.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The team did not use the name in a formal sense until 1916, when the name was printed on home World Series programs.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The word "Dodgers" appeared on team jerseys in 1932.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The "conclusive shift" came in 1933, when both home and road jerseys for the team bore the name "Dodgers".
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Examples of how the many popularized names of the team were used interchangeably are available from newspaper articles from the period before 1932.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Most baseball statistics sites and baseball historians generally now refer to the pennant-winning 1916 Brooklyn team as the Robins; on the other hand, the *Brooklyn Daily Eagle* used "Superbas" in its box scores that season.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] A 1918 *New York Times* article used the nickname Robins in its title "Buccaneers Take Last From Robins", but the subtitle of the article reads "Subdue The Superbas By 11 To 4, Making Series An Even Break".
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Space-conscious headline writers still used "the Flock" (derived from "Robins") during the Dodgers' last decade in Brooklyn.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Another example of the interchangeability of different nicknames is found on the program issued at Ebbets Field for the 1920 World Series, which identifies the matchup in the series as "Dodgers vs.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Indians", despite the fact that the Robins nickname had been in consistent usage at this point for around six years.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] For most of the first half of the 20th century, no Major League Baseball team employed a black player.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] A parallel system of Negro leagues developed, but most Negro league players were denied a chance to prove their skill before a wider national audience.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Jackie Robinson became the first African-American to play in MLB in the 20th century when he played his first NL game on April 15, 1947 for the Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Robinson's entry into the league was mainly due to general manager Branch Rickey's efforts.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The deeply religious Rickey's motivation appears to have been primarily moral, although business considerations were also present.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Rickey was a member of the Methodist Church, the antecedent denomination to the United Methodist Church of today, which was a strong advocate for social justice and active later in the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Rickey saw his opportunity with the 1944 death of Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis, an arch-segregationist and enforcer of the color barrier.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Besides selecting Robinson for his exceptional baseball skills, Rickey also considered Robinson's outstanding personal character, his UCLA education and rank of captain in the U.S.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Army in his decision, since he knew that boos, taunts, and criticism were going to be directed at Robinson, and that Robinson had to be tough enough to withstand abuse without attempting to retaliate.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The inclusion of Robinson on the team also led the Dodgers to move its spring training site.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Prior to 1946, the Dodgers held their spring training in Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] However, the city's stadium refused to host an exhibition game with the Montreal Royals, the Dodgers' own farm club, on whose roster Robinson appeared at the time, citing segregation laws.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Ultimately, City Island Ballpark in Daytona Beach agreed to host the game with Robinson on the field.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The team traveled to Havana, Cuba for spring training in 1947, this time with Robinson on the big club.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Although the Dodgers ultimately built Dodgertown and its Holman Stadium further south in Vero Beach, and played there for 61 spring training seasons from 1948 through 2008, Daytona Beach renamed City Island Ballpark to Jackie Robinson Ballpark in his honor.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] This event marked the continuation of the integration of professional sports in the United States, with professional football having led the way in 1946, with the concomitant demise of the Negro leagues, and is regarded as a key moment in the history of the American civil rights movement.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Robinson was an exceptional player, a speedy runner who sparked the team with his intensity.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] He was the inaugural recipient of the Rookie of the Year award, which is now named the Jackie Robinson award in his honor.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers' willingness to integrate, when most other teams refused to, was a key factor in their 1947–1956 success.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] They won six pennants in those 10 years with the help of Robinson, three-time MVP Roy Campanella, Cy Young Award winner Don Newcombe, Jim Gilliam, and Joe Black.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Robinson eventually became the first African-American elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1962.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] After the wilderness years of the 1920s and 1930s, the Dodgers were rebuilt into a contending club first by general manager Larry MacPhail and then the legendary Branch Rickey.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The annual ritual of building excitement, followed in the end by disappointment, became a common pattern to the long suffering fans, and **"Wait 'til next year!"** became an unofficial Dodger slogan.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] While the Dodgers generally enjoyed success during this period, in 1951 they fell victim to one of the largest collapses in the history of baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] On August 11, 1951, Brooklyn led the National League by an enormous 13+1⁄2 games over their archrivals, the Giants.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] While the Dodgers went 26–22 from that time until the end of the season, the Giants went on to win 37 of their last 44 games, including their last seven in a row.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] At the end of the season the Dodgers and the Giants were tied for first place, forcing a three-game playoff for the pennant.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Giants took Game 1 by a score of 3–1 before being shut out by the Dodgers' Clem Labine in Game 2, 10–0.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Brooklyn held a 4–2 lead in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 3.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Giants outfielder Bobby Thomson, however, hit a stunning three-run walk-off home run off the Dodgers' Ralph Branca to secure the NL Championship for the Giants.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Thomson's home run is known as the Shot Heard 'Round The World.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1955, by which time the core of the Dodger team was beginning to age, "next year" finally came.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The fabled "Boys of Summer" shot down the "Bronx Bombers" in seven games, led by the first-class pitching of young left-hander Johnny Podres, whose key pitch was a changeup known as "pulling down the lampshade" because of the arm motion used right when the ball was released.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Podres won two Series games, including the deciding seventh.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The turning point of Game 7 was a spectacular double play that began with left fielder Sandy Amorós running down Yogi Berra's long fly ball, then throwing to shortstop Pee Wee Reese, who relayed to first baseman Gil Hodges to double up a surprised Gil McDougald to preserve the Dodger lead.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Hank Bauer grounded out and the Dodgers won 2–0.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Although the Dodgers lost the World Series to the Yankees in 1956, during which the Yankees pitcher Don Larsen pitched the only World Series perfect game in baseball history and the only post-season no-hitter for the next 54 years, it hardly seemed to matter.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Lawyer and real estate businessman Walter O'Malley had acquired majority ownership of the Dodgers in 1950, when he bought Rickey's 25 percent share of the team and secured the support of the widow of another equal partner, John L.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Soon O'Malley was working to buy new land in Brooklyn for a new, more accessible and better ballpark than Ebbets Field.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Beloved as it was, Ebbets Field had grown old and was not well served by vehicular infrastructure, to the point where the Dodgers could not "sell out" the park to maximum capacity even in the heat of a pennant race, despite dominating the league from 1946 to 1957.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] New York City Construction Coordinator Robert Moses sought to force O'Malley into using a site in Flushing Meadows, Queens – the eventual location of Shea Stadium (which opened in 1964), the home of the future New York Mets, who began play in 1962.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Moses' vision involved a city-built, city-owned park, which was greatly at odds with O'Malley's real-estate savvy.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] When O'Malley realized that he was not going to be allowed to buy a suitable parcel of land in Brooklyn, he began thinking of moving the team.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] O'Malley was free to purchase land of his own choosing but wanted Moses to condemn a parcel of land along the Atlantic Railroad Yards in downtown Brooklyn under Title I authority, after O'Malley had bought the bulk of the land he had in mind.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Title I gave the city power to condemn land for the purpose of building what it calls "public purpose" projects.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Moses' interpretation of "public purpose" included public parks, housing, highways, and bridges.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] What O'Malley wanted was for Moses to use Title I authority, rather than to pay market value for the land.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] With Title I the city via Robert Moses could have sold the land to O'Malley at a below market price.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Meanwhile, non-stop transcontinental airline travel had become routine during the years since World War II.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Teams were no longer bound by much slower railroad infrastructure.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Because of advances in civil aviation, it became possible to locate teams farther apart, as far west as California, while maintaining the same game schedules.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] When Los Angeles officials attended the 1956 World Series looking to entice a team to move there, they were not even thinking of the Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Their original target had been the Washington Senators franchise, which eventually moved to Bloomington, Minnesota to become the Minnesota Twins in 1961.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] At the same time, O'Malley was looking for a contingency in case Moses and other New York politicians refused to let him build the Brooklyn stadium he wanted and sent word to the Los Angeles officials that he was interested in talking.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Los Angeles offered him what New York did not: a chance to buy land somewhat suitable for building a ballpark and the chance to own that ballpark, giving him complete control over all its revenue streams.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] At the same time, the National League was not willing to approve the Dodgers' move unless O'Malley found a second team willing to join them out west, largely out of concern for travel costs.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Meanwhile, Giants owner Horace Stoneham was having similar difficulty finding a replacement for his team's antiquated home stadium, the Polo Grounds.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Unlike O'Malley, Stoneham did not engage in a serious effort to identify a location for a replacement for the Polo Grounds.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Stoneham was considering moving the Giants to Minneapolis but was persuaded instead to move them to San Francisco, ensuring that the Dodgers had a National League rival closer than St.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] So, the two arch-rival teams, the Dodgers and Giants, moved out to the West Coast together after the 1957 season.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Brooklyn Dodgers played their final game at Ebbets Field on September 24, 1957, which the Dodgers won 2–0 over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] On April 18, 1958, the Los Angeles Dodgers played their first game in L.A., defeating the former New York and newly moved and renamed San Francisco Giants, 6–5, before 78,672 fans at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Catcher Roy Campanella, left partially paralyzed in an off-season automobile accident on January 28, 1958, never played for the Dodgers in Los Angeles.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] With the threat of a New York team joining the new Continental League, the National League expanded by adding the New York Mets following a proposal from William Shea.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In a symbolic reference to New York's earlier National League teams, the new team took as its primary colors the blue of the Dodgers and the orange of the Giants, both of which are colors also featured on the flag of New York City.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The historic and heated rivalry between the Dodgers and the Giants is more than a century old.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] It began when the Dodgers and Giants faced each other in the 1889 World Series, the ancestor of the Subway Series, and both played in separate, neighboring cities.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Brooklyn and New York were separate cities until 1898, when they became neighboring boroughs of the newly consolidated New York City.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] When both franchises moved to California after the 1957 season, the rivalry was easily transplanted, as the cities of Los Angeles and San Francisco have long been economic, political, and cultural rivals, representative of the broader Southern/Northern California divide.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Manager Wilbert Robinson, another former Oriole, popularly known as "Uncle Robbie", restored the Brooklyn team to respectability.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] His "Brooklyn Robins" reached the 1916 and 1920 World Series, losing both, but contending perennially for several seasons.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Charles Ebbets and Ed McKeever died within a week of each other in 1925, and Robbie was named president while still field manager.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Upon assuming the title of president, however, Robinson's ability to focus on the field declined, and the teams of the late 1920s were often fondly referred to as the "Daffiness Boys" for their distracted, error-ridden style of play.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Outfielder Babe Herman was the leader both in hitting and in zaniness.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The signature Dodger play from this era occurred when three players, Dazzy Vance, Chick Fewster, and Herman, ended up at third base at the same time.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The play is often remembered as Herman "tripling into a triple play", though only two of the three players were declared out and Herman was credited with a double rather than a triple.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Herman later complained that no one remembered that he drove in the winning run on the play.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] After his removal as club president, Robinson returned to managing, and the club's performance rebounded somewhat.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] When Robinson retired in 1931, he was replaced as manager by Max Carey, who had played for the team from 1926 until 1929.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Although some suggested renaming the "Robins" the "Brooklyn Canaries", after Carey, whose last name was originally "Carnarius", the name "Brooklyn Dodgers" returned to stay following Robinson's retirement.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] It was during this era that Willard Mullin, a noted sports cartoonist, fixed the Brooklyn team with the lovable nickname of "Dem Bums".
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] After hearing his cab driver ask, "So how did those bums do today?", Mullin decided to sketch an exaggerated version of famed circus clown Emmett Kelly to represent the Dodgers in his much-praised cartoons in the *New York World-Telegram*.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Both image and nickname caught on, so much so that many a Dodger yearbook cover, from 1951 through 1957, featured a Willard Mullin illustration of the Brooklyn Bum.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Perhaps the highlight of the Daffiness Boys era came after Wilbert Robinson left the dugout.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] As it happened, the season entered its final games with the Giants tied with the St.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Louis Cardinals for the pennant, with the Giants' remaining games against the Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Stengel led his Bums to the Polo Grounds for the showdown, and they beat the Giants twice to knock them out of the pennant race.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The "Gashouse Gang" Cardinals nailed the pennant by beating the Cincinnati Reds those same two days.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] One key development during this era was the 1938 appointment of Leland "Larry" MacPhail as Dodgers' general manager.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] MacPhail, who brought night games to Major League Baseball as general manager of the Reds, also started night baseball in Brooklyn and ordered the successful refurbishing of Ebbets Field.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] He also brought Reds voice Red Barber to Brooklyn as the Dodgers' lead announcer in 1939, just after MacPhail broke the New York baseball executives' agreement to ban live baseball broadcasts, enacted because of the fear of the effect of radio calls on the home teams' attendance.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] MacPhail remained with the Dodgers until 1942, when he returned to the Armed Forces for World War II.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] He later became one of the Yankees' co-owners, bidding unsuccessfully for Barber to join him in the Bronx as announcer.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The first major-league baseball game to be televised was Brooklyn's 6–1 victory over Cincinnati at Ebbets Field on August 26, 1939.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Batting helmets were introduced to Major League Baseball by the Dodgers in 1941.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers met the Yankees, another New York team, seven times in the World Series, more than any other two teams from the American and National Leagues before 1958.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Yankees are 6–1 against the Brooklyn Dodgers in the World Series, with the Dodgers winning their first and only World Series title against the Yankees, four games to three, in 1955.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] After the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles in 1958, the rivalry continued as the teams met five more times in the World Series and represented two of the largest cities on each coast of the United States.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Since 1958, the Dodgers have improved their record against the Yankees in the World Series; they are currently leading 3–2.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Fan support has added to the notoriety of the series as both teams are supported by two of the largest fanbases in North America.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Although the rivalry's significance arose from the two teams' numerous World Series meetings, the Yankees and Dodgers did not meet in the World Series between 1981 and 2024.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] They did not play each other again in a non-exhibition game until 2004, when they played a three-game interleague series.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Nevertheless, games between the two teams have drawn sellout crowds.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Cardinals–Dodgers rivalry was particularly intense from 1941 through 1949.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1942 the Cardinals overcame a 10 game Dodger lead in early August to win the pennant.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1946 the Cardinals and Dodgers finished the regular season tied for first place but the Cardinals won the pennant when they prevailed in the first ever playoff tiebreaker in the National League.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] During this period, after the 1942 season, Branch Rickey, who had built up the Cardinals farm system as their general manager moved to become the Dodgers' general manager.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1947, after Rickey broke the color line by signing Jackie Robinson to the Dodgers, there were rumors that southerners playing for the Cardinals were planning to boycott games against the Dodgers, although the players later denied it.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In general, the Cardinals were latecomers to integration.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Front-office executive Bing Devine said the owner from 1947 to 1953, Fred Saigh, refused to sign black players.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Louis was, in many ways, a Southern city.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In the mid-1950s many of its stores and restaurants refused to serve black customers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Cardinals, with baseball's largest radio network blanketing the Midwest and South, had cultivated white Southern fans.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Their ballpark was also the last in the majors to abolish segregated seating.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Because of their lack of black players, the Cardinals play suffered on the field tremendously in the 1950s.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Meanwhile, with the success of Robinson, the Dodgers doubled down on the opportunity to sign players of color from the Negro leagues.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In the subsequent years after their pennant-winning season in 1947, they would sign Don Newcombe, Roy Campanella, and Jim Gilliam from the Negro leagues, adding to an already tremendous team.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers made the World Series in 1949, 1952, 1953, 1955, and 1956 (winning championships in 1955) and were a historic pennant race away from making it in 1951, in part because they were the first to accept African American players.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The 1951 season included a 14-game winning streak for the Dodgers against the Cardinals, the longest such streak in the rivalry.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The Dodgers have retired seven numbers in the history of the franchise related to its tenure in Brooklyn.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The following are of those whose contributions to the Dodgers took place either entirely or significantly in Brooklyn.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 1997, 50 years after he broke the color barrier and 25 years after the Dodgers retired his number, Robinson's No.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] 42 was retired throughout Major League Baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Robinson is the only major league baseball player so honored.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Starting in the 2007 season, Jackie Robinson Day (April 15, commemorating the Opening Day of Robinson's rookie season of 1947) has featured many or all players and coaches wearing the number 42 as a tribute to Robinson.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In 2019, the Dodgers established "Legends of Dodger Baseball", which is meant to honor Dodger greats whose numbers have not been retired.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] The program honors those who made an "impact on the franchise, both on and off the field." Recipients are recognized with plaques at Dodger Stadium.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] Of these players, only one was primarily a Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] A 2007 HBO film, *Brooklyn Dodgers: The Ghosts of Flatbush*, is a documentary covering the Dodgers history from early days to the beginning of the Los Angeles era.
[src:benny-meyer/brooklyn-dodgers] In the film, the story is related that O'Malley was so hated by Brooklyn Dodger fans after the move to California, that it was said: "If you asked a Brooklyn Dodger fan, if you had a gun with only two bullets in it and were in a room with Hitler, Stalin, and O'Malley, who would you shoot?
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Hired by the Senators to act as player-manager at the age of 27, Harris would lead the team to the 1924 World Series title, becoming the youngest manager to win a championship and the first rookie manager to do so (four other rookies have accomplished the feat since).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris managed 29 seasons, fourth most in MLB history.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Stanley Raymond "Bucky" Harris was born on November 8, 1896, in Port Jervis, New York, and raised after the age of six in Pittston, Pennsylvania.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His father, Thomas, had emigrated from Wales, while his mother, Catherine (Rupp), hailed from Hughestown, near Pittston.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His elder brother, Merle, was a minor league second baseman.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Bucky Harris left school at age 13 to work at a local colliery, the Butler Mine, as an office boy and, later, a weigh master.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In his spare time, Harris played basketball for the Pittston YMCA team as well as sandlot baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris was listed as 5 feet 9 inches (1.75 m) tall and 156 pounds (71 kg); he threw and batted right-handed.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In 1916, when Harris was 19, Pittston native Hughie Jennings, then the manager of the Detroit Tigers, signed him to his first contract and farmed him to the Class B Muskegon Reds of the Central League, where he struggled as a batsman and was released.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris then caught on with the Scranton Miners, Norfolk Tars and Reading Pretzels through 1917, before reaching the highest level of minor league baseball with the 1918–1919 Buffalo Bisons of the International League.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris improved his batting skills during the latter season with the Bisons, making 126 hits and raising his average to .282.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris then was recommended to the Washington Senators by baseball promoter Joe Engel, who led the Chattanooga Lookouts at Engel Stadium.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In August 1919, at the age of 22, he came up to Washington but was unimpressive at first, batting a meager .214 and getting into only eight games that first season.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris spent most of his playing career as a second baseman with the Senators (1919–1928).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In 1924, he was named player-manager; at the age of 27 he was the youngest manager in the Majors.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] These feats are even more impressive considering that the light-hitting Harris only hit nine home runs during his entire career.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] After Harris‘ back-to-back pennants in 1924–1925, he was able to keep the Senators in the first division for the next three seasons, but their win totals declined, from 96 (1925) to 81 (1926), then 85 (1927).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] When, in 1928, they won only 75 games (against 79 losses), Griffith traded Harris to Detroit and changed managers, with Hall of Fame pitcher Walter Johnson named as his successor.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] The 1928 Tigers had won only 68 games, and Harris' 1929 edition offered only a slight improvement, winning 70.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris’ initial departure from the Senators in 1928 (he would twice return to manage them again from 1935 to 1942 and 1950–1954) came in a trade to the Tigers as player-manager.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Although he retired as a player after the 1931 season, his playing career effectively ended with his trade to Detroit.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris only made 11 cameo appearances in the Tiger lineup: seven in 1929 and four in 1931.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In all, he appeared in 1,263 games over all or portions of 13 seasons, and collected 1,297 hits, with 224 doubles, 64 triples, nine home runs, 472 bases on balls, and 167 stolen bases.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris batted .274 lifetime with 508 career runs batted in.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In five full seasons as the Tigers' manager, he produced only one winning year, 1932, when Detroit went 76–75 and finished fifth and 29+1⁄2 games behind the Yankees.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In the waning days of 1933, Harris stepped down.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His eventual successor, Mickey Cochrane, a future Hall-of-Fame catcher who was acquired from the Philadelphia Athletics, would lead the Tigers as a player-manager to back-to-back pennants in 1934–1935 (and their first-ever world championship in the latter year).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris signed as manager of the Red Sox for 1934.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Boston was then a habitual tail-ender in the American League, and had registered 15 consecutive losing seasons since its 1918 world championship.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] The 1933 Red Sox had won only 63 games and finished seventh in the eight-team AL under Marty McManus, but their wealthy new owner, Tom Yawkey, had begun a major rebuilding of both the ball club and Fenway Park.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Yawkey jettisoned McManus and personally selected Harris as his new manager, and his 1934 Red Sox, despite an injury-riddled season by newly purchased ace left-handed pitcher Lefty Grove, broke the losing-season streak, finishing at .500 (76–76).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] But Harris's stay in the Boston dugout lasted only one season.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] He and Eddie Collins, the Red Sox' general manager, had feuded since their playing days and Yawkey may have hired Harris without consulting Collins.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] When Joe Cronin, the hard-hitting, 28-year-old playing manager of the Senators, became available on the trade market, Yawkey and Collins moved quickly, sending shortstop Lyn Lary and $225,000 to Washington on October 26, 1934, for Cronin, and then naming him manager for 1935.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris then took Cronin's old job, returning to Clark Griffith and the Senators.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris' second term in Washington lasted for eight seasons (1935–1942), his longest tenure as a skipper.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] However, he never approached the highs of 1924 or 1925.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Only one of his teams, the 1936 Senators, had a winning record (82–71) and first-division finish.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris kept the club out of the American League basement, but three consecutive seventh-place finishes from 1940 to 1942 led to his departure.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His only season in the National League was spent as skipper of the 1943 Phillies.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Perhaps the worst team (42–109, .278) in baseball in 1942, the Phillies had just been sold to lumberman William D.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Under Harris, the 1943 edition improved to play .424 baseball (39–53) by July 27, with just three fewer victories than they had in all of 1942.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] However, Harris chafed at Cox' constant interference.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] When Harris protested, Cox abruptly fired him after only 92 games.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris then played a role in Cox' banishment from professional baseball for betting on games.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] On the day after his firing, Harris dropped a bombshell at his hotel room — he had evidence that Cox was betting on baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris's friends, outraged at his firing, informed Commissioner of Baseball Kenesaw Mountain Landis that Cox was violating baseball's anti-gambling mandate.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Landis then summoned Harris to his office to testify in person about Cox' behavior.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] The owner was suspended indefinitely three months later and banned from baseball outright soon afterward.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris then spent three seasons out of the big leagues, serving as general manager (1944–1946) and field manager (1944–1945) of the Buffalo Bisons, his old team in the International League.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In August 1946, the Yankees' co-owner and GM, Larry MacPhail, appointed Harris to a front-office position.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] The tumultuous 1946 season saw MacPhail employ three managers — Joe McCarthy, Bill Dickey and Johnny Neun — and finish third, 17 games in arrears of the pennant-winning Red Sox.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] At the close of the season, MacPhail named Harris the Bombers' 1947 manager, and he led them to his third American League pennant — the Yankees' 15th league title.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Behind Most Valuable Player Joe DiMaggio and newly acquired starting pitcher Allie Reynolds, the 1947 Yanks won 97 games and prevailed over the Tigers by a 12-game margin.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Then they won Harris's second World Series championship, defeating the Jackie Robinson-led Brooklyn Dodgers in a thrilling, seven-game Fall Classic.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] MacPhail sold his stake in the Yankees and left baseball immediately after the 1947 Series and Harris returned for a second season as manager.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His 1948 Yankees won 94 games to finish a close third in a hectic pennant race, two games behind the Cleveland Indians and Red Sox, who ended the regular season in a tie for first place.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] But the result dissatisfied the Yankees' post-MacPhail ownership team, Dan Topping and Del Webb, and their new general manager, George Weiss, and they replaced Harris with Casey Stengel.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Stengel would lead New York to ten American League pennants and seven World Series titles in the next 12 seasons.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris returned to the minor leagues in 1949 as manager of the San Diego Padres of the Pacific Coast League, before launching his third stint as skipper of the Senators, coming off a 104-loss 1949 season.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His first campaign, 1950, saw a 17-game improvement for Washington, then he led the Senators to a winning (78–76) mark in 1952, but the team could not escape the second division in Harris's five-year, final term as Washington's manager.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Nevertheless, the Tigers chose Harris to replace Fred Hutchinson as their manager for 1955, and in the first season of his second term in Detroit, Harris again produced a turnaround.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] The 1955 Tigers won 79 games (eleven more than 1954's edition) and had their first above-.500 season since 1950.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Pitcher Ned Garver described Harris as "sympathetic," recalling that he would wait until an inning was over before replacing a pitcher on the mound.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] But the Tigers finished fifth each season, and were experiencing turmoil in their front office; outspoken owner Walter Briggs Jr. was harshly critical of Harris and his coaches during the season and was in the process of selling the team.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Fired by new owner Fred Knorr, Harris closed out his 29-year MLB managing career with a win–loss record of 2,158–2,219 (.493).
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] As of September 2019, Harris ranked seventh in MLB manager career wins.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] In 1957, at 60, Harris rejoined the Red Sox in a front office capacity.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] He was assistant general manager to Joe Cronin for two seasons, and then, when Cronin was named president of the American League, succeeded him as GM in January 1959, 24 years after Cronin had displaced Harris as Boston's field manager.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris served for two losing seasons as general manager of the Red Sox before his firing in late September 1960.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] On his watch, the Red Sox finally broke the baseball color line by promoting Pumpsie Green from Triple-A on July 21, 1959, more than a dozen years after Robinson's debut with the Dodgers.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] They were the last of the 16 pre-expansion teams to integrate.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] But the Red Sox went 75–79 in 1959 and fell into the second division, beginning a streak of eight straight losing seasons.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Then, in 1960, Hall of Famer Ted Williams's final season, they won only 65 games and finished seventh in the eight-team league.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Rightfielder Jackie Jensen, still productive at age 33 — he had been 1958's American League MVP and the AL's 1959 runs batted in leader — sat out the entire 1960 campaign in retirement due to his fear of flying.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris made a flurry of minor trades in an attempt to shake up his faltering team.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] His two highest-profile transactions, which occurred during the 1959–1960 offseason, saw him send left-handed pitcher and former bonus baby Frank Baumann to the Chicago White Sox and veteran starting catcher Sammy White to the Indians.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] But Baumann led the AL in earned run average with the 1960 Chisox (while the player Harris obtained, first baseman Ron Jackson, struggled through only ten games with Boston before being traded away again) and White abruptly retired rather than report to Cleveland, canceling his trade.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris also ran afoul of Yawkey when he fired Yawkey associate Pinky Higgins as manager and replaced him with Billy Jurges, a Senators' coach, on July 3, 1959, without consulting the owner.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Jurges lasted less than a calendar year as the Red Sox' pilot before his firing in June 1960 — and replacement by Higgins.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris's dismissal followed not quite four months later.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris ended his long MLB career as a scout for the White Sox (1961–1962) and special assistant for the new expansion Washington Senators franchise that played in D.C. from 1961 to 1971 before moving on to Arlington, Texas.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] All told, he spent over 55 years in baseball.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] He died in Bethesda, Maryland, on his 81st birthday.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] According to his obituary in the November 10, 1977 Washington Post, Harris died after a long battle with Parkinson's disease.
[src:benny-meyer/bucky-harris] Harris's father-in-law during his first marriage, which ended in divorce in 1951, was Howard Sutherland, former United States Senator from West Virginia.
